VWhat was the most difficult job you ever did?
p4
aVWas it working in the sun?
p5
aVWas it working to provide food for a family or a community?
p6
aVWas it working days and nights trying to protect lives and property?
p7
aVWas it working alone
p8
aVor working on a project that wasn't guaranteed to succeed,
p9
aVbut that might improve human health or save a life?
p10
aVWas it working to build something, create something, make a work of art?
p11
aVWas it work for which you were never sure
p12
aVyou were fully understood or appreciated?
p13
aVThe people in our communities who do these jobs
p14
aVdeserve our attention, our love and our deepest support.
p15
aa(lp16
VBut people aren't the only ones in our communities
p17
aVwho do these difficult jobs.
p18
aVThese jobs are also done by the plants, the animals
p19
aVand the ecosystems on our planet,
p20
aVincluding the ecosystems I study: the tropical coral reefs.
p21
aVCoral reefs are farmers.
p22
aVThey provide food, income and food security
p23
aVfor hundreds of millions of people around the world.
p24
aVCoral reefs are security guards.
p25
aVThe structures that they build protect our shorelines
p26
aVfrom storm surge and waves,
p27
aVand the biological systems that they house filter the water
p28
aVand make it safer for us to work and play.
p29
aVCoral reefs are chemists.
p30
aVThe molecules that we're discovering on coral reefs are increasingly important
p31
aVin the search for new antibiotics and new cancer drugs.
p32
aVAnd coral reefs are artists.
p33
aVThe structures that they build
p34
aVare some of the most beautiful things on planet Earth.
p35
aVAnd this beauty is the foundation of the tourism industry
p36
aVin many countries with few or little other natural resources.
p37
aa(lp38
VSo for all of these reasons, all of these ecosystem services,
p39
aVeconomists estimate the value of the world's coral reefs
p40
aVin the hundreds of billions of dollars per year.
p41
aVAnd yet despite all that hard work being done for us
p42
aVand all that wealth that we gain,
p43
aVwe have done almost everything we possibly could to destroy that.
p44
aVWe have taken the fish out of the oceans
p45
aVand we have added in fertilizer, sewage,
p46
aVdiseases, oil, pollution, sediments.
p47
aVWe have trampled the reefs physically with our boats, our fins, our bulldozers,
p48
aVand we have changed the chemistry of the entire sea,
p49
aVwarmed the waters and made storms worse.
p50
aVAnd these would all be bad on their own,
p51
aVbut these threats magnify each other
p52
aVand compound one another and make each other worse.
p53
aa(lp54
VI'll give you an example.
p55
aVWhere I live and work, in Curaçao, a tropical storm went by a few years ago.
p56
aVAnd on the eastern end of the island,
p57
aVwhere the reefs are intact and thriving,
p58
aVyou could barely tell a tropical storm had passed.
p59
aVBut in town, where corals had died from overfishing, from pollution,
p60
aVthe tropical storm picked up the dead corals
p61
aVand used them as bludgeons to kill the corals that were left.
p62
aVThis is a coral that I studied during my PhD \u2014
p63
aVI got to know it quite well.
p64
aVAnd after this storm took off half of its tissue,
p65
aVit became infested with algae,
p66
aVthe algae overgrew the tissue and that coral died.
p67
aVThis magnification of threats, this compounding of factors
p68
aVis what Jeremy Jackson describes as the "slippery slope to slime."
p69
aVIt's hardly even a metaphor because many of our reefs now
p70
aVare literally bacteria and algae and slime.
