aa(lp90
VSo let's change that.
p91
aVWhat is a coral and where does it come from?
p92
aVCorals are born in a number of different ways,
p93
aVbut most often by mass spawning: all of the individuals of a single species
p94
aVon one night a year,
p95
aVreleasing all the eggs they've made that year
p96
aVinto the water column,
p97
aVpackaged into bundles with sperm cells.
p98
aVAnd those bundles go to the surface of the ocean and break apart.
p99
aVAnd hopefully \u2014 hopefully \u2014 at the surface of the ocean,
p100
aVthey meet the eggs and sperm from other corals.
p101
aVAnd that is why you need lots of corals on a coral reef \u2014
p102
aVso that all of their eggs can meet their match at the surface.
p103
aVWhen they're fertilized, they do what any other animal egg does:
p104
aVdivides in half again and again and again.
p105
aVTaking these photos under the microscope every year
p106
aVis one of my favorite and most magical moments of the year.
p107
aVAt the end of all this cell division, they turn into a swimming larva \u2014
p108
aVa little tiny blob of fat the size of a poppy seed,
p109
aVbut with all of the sensory systems that we have.
p110
aVThey can sense color and light, textures, chemicals, pH.
p111
aVThey can even feel pressure waves; they can hear sound.
p112
aVAnd they use those talents
p113
aVto search the bottom of the reef for a place to attach
p114
aVand live the rest of their lives.
p115
aa(lp116
VSo imagine finding a place where you would live the rest of your life
p117
aVwhen you were just two days old.
p118
aVThey attach in the place they find most suitable,
p119
aVthey build a skeleton underneath themselves,
p120
aVthey build a mouth and tentacles,
p121
aVand then they begin the difficult work of building the world's coral reefs.
p122
aVOne coral polyp will divide itself again and again and again,
p123
aVleaving a limestone skeleton underneath itself
p124
aVand growing up toward the sun.
p125
aVGiven hundreds of years and many species,
p126
aVwhat you get is a massive limestone structure
p127
aVthat can be seen from space in many cases,
p128
aVcovered by a thin skin of these hardworking animals.
p129
aVNow, there are only a few hundred species of corals on the planet, maybe 1,000.
p130
aVBut these systems house millions and millions of other species,
p131
aVand that diversity is what stabilizes the systems,
p132
aVand it's where we're finding our new medicines.
p133
aVIt's how we find new sources of food.
p134
aVI'm lucky enough to work on the island of Curaçao,
p135
aVwhere we still have reefs that look like this.
p136
aVBut, indeed, much of the Caribbean and much of our world
p137
aVis much more like this.
