aa(lp161
VA few years ago we took a 3D printer and we made coral choice surveys \u2014
p162
aVdifferent colors and different textures,
p163
aVand we simply asked the coral where they preferred to settle.
p164
aVAnd we found that corals, even without the biology involved,
p165
aVstill prefer white and pink, the colors of a healthy reef.
p166
aVAnd they prefer crevices and grooves and holes,
p167
aVwhere they will be safe from being trampled
p168
aVor eaten by a predator.
p169
aVSo we can use this knowledge,
p170
aVwe can go back and say we need to restore those factors \u2014
p171
aVthat pink, that white, those crevices, those hard surfaces \u2014
p172
aVin our conservation projects.
p173
aVWe can also use that knowledge
p174
aVif we're going to put something underwater, like a sea wall or a pier.
p175
aVWe can choose to use the materials and colors and textures
p176
aVthat might bias the system back toward those corals.
p177
aVNow in addition to the surfaces,
p178
aVwe also study the chemical and microbial signals
p179
aVthat attract corals to reefs.
p180
aVStarting about six years ago, I began culturing bacteria
p181
aVfrom surfaces where corals had settled.
p182
aVAnd I tried those one by one by one,
p183
aVlooking for the bacteria that would convince corals to settle and attach.
p184
aVAnd we now have many bacterial strains in our freezer
p185
aVthat will reliably cause corals
p186
aVto go through that settlement and attachment process.
p187
aVSo as we speak,
p188
aVmy colleagues in Curaçao are testing those bacteria
p189
aVto see if they'll help us raise more coral settlers in the lab,
p190
aVand to see if those coral settlers will survive better
p191
aVwhen we put them back underwater.
p192
aa(lp193
VNow in addition to these tools, we also try to uncover the mysteries
p194
aVof species that are under-studied.
p195
aVThis is one of my favorite corals, and always has been:
p196
aVdendrogyra cylindrus, the pillar coral.
p197
aVI love it because it makes this ridiculous shape,
p198
aVbecause its tentacles are fat and look fuzzy
p199
aVand because it's rare.
p200
aVFinding one of these on a reef is a treat.
p201
aVIn fact, it's so rare,
p202
aVthat last year it was listed as a threatened species
p203
aVon the endangered species list.
p204
aVAnd this was in part because in over 30 years of research surveys,
p205
aVscientists had never found a baby pillar coral.
p206
aVWe weren't even sure if they could still reproduce,
p207
aVor if they were still reproducing.
